<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-668-216  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 668 216.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 18 1989 v6 n37 p37(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bug undermines performance: DataEases International Inc.,andO;GrafTalk, $395. (Software Review) (one of four evaluations)(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Halliday, Caroline; Erickson, Michelle.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>DataEase International's $395 GrafTalk targets developers who wantto incorporate its graphics features into other products.andP;  It canbe used as a stand-alone linked to 1-2-3.andP;  A bug in the menusystem prevents chart parameters such as the scaling setting forthe shading of bars in a bar graph from being preserved duringrestoration.andP;  This flaw occurs when a chart is created and savedin the menu-driven mode and retrieved from disk.andP;  The menu iswell-structured and comfortable, and the entire 1-2-3 spreadsheet,or just a part of it, can be imported.andP;  A chart can be updated bysaving the chart without the data, retrieving it and importing thedata.andP;  No PostScript devices are supported by GrafTalk.andP;  Usershave found that learning the command language is difficult butworth the effort.andP;  GrafTalk does not interface well withDataEase's database.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dataease International Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 (Spreadsheet software) (computer programs)GrafTalk (Computer graphics software).andO;Topic:     EvaluationSoftware packagesGraphics Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Bug Undermines PerformanceandM;DATAEASE INTERNATIONAL INC.,andM;GRAFTALK, $395andM;GrafTalk is marketed primarily to developers who incorporate its graphicscapabilities into other applications, such as databases or C language-basedproducts.andP;  A secondary market also exists as an add-in product with theDataEase database, which is used extensively in government installations.andM;PC Week tested it as a stand-alone product to meet the 1-2-3 spreadsheetlinking and printing criteria.andM;Of the products reviewed, GrafTalk is the weakest.andP;  It can link to 1-2-3spreadsheets and provides automated batch printing, but not as cleanly as theother products.andP;  In addition, a serious bug in the menu system surfacedduring testing.andM;When a chart is created, saved and retrieved from disk using the menu-drivenmode, some chart parameters are not preserved during the restore process.andM;For example, a scaling setting for the shading of bars in a bar chart appearscorrect in the listed option, but is not present when previewed and printed.andO;Charts created via the command-prompt mode did not suffer from this problem.andM;DataEase officials acknowledged the bug, but did not say when an upgradewould be available.andM;The command-prompt mode gives access to a command batch language withextensive graph-creation capabilities.andP;  The menu-driven system has acomfortable feel and is well-structured.andM;Users can link a graph with a 1-2-3 spreadsheet from the menu mode.andP;  Theentire spreadsheet, or a single area within the spreadsheet (specified bycell addresses) can be imported.andM;Updating a chart with new data from the spreadsheet requires saving the chartwithout the data, retrieving the saved chart and reimporting the data.andM;Batch printing of numerous graphs requires use of the command-promptlanguage.andP;  A file containing commands that set the parameters for each graph,import the 1-2-3 data and then print the graph is necessary.andP;  Once created,the file can be run to produce the output.andM;GrafTalk does not support Apple Computer Inc.andP;  LaserWriter or otherPostScript devices; nor does it support any image recorders.andM;DataEase International Inc., of Trumbull, Conn., can be reached at (203)374-8000.andM;----------Buyers say: Good but difficultandM;&quot;You have to put a lot of time into GrafTalk because it's a programminglanguage, but it's well worth the time and effort to learn the commandlanguage.andP;  Your output will show the effort invested,&quot; said Bob Parker,president of Emily Toys Inc., a toy manufacturer in Brookfield Center, Conn.andO;Parker considered other packages but chose GrafTalk because it is both menu-and command-driven.andM;&quot;It's very easy to position and size graphs,&quot; Parker added.andP;  &quot;You can createa command routine to do batch printing, which is a real plus.andP;  I'd like tosee a 3-D capability added to it.&quot;andM;After using the DataEase database, Dr.andP;  Martin Goldstein, medical director atDiagnostic Imaging Center Inc., in Miami, chose the companion graphicspackage.andM;However, he has found GrafTalk difficult to use and was forced to abandondevelopment of a commercial application that was to merge the two products.andM;&quot;There are a lot of tiny steps you have to go through to get a graph, andthat defeats the purpose of the menu system,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;I think [GrafTalk]is a poorly conceived, poorly executed and poorly documented product.andP;  It'sextremely difficult to use and interfaces very poorly with DataEase'sdatabase product.&quot;andM;</TEXT></DOC>